tspan.tspan: The Democratic Party has been crushing the GOP
for the past eight years in terms of Americans who
affiliate with their party.
But that means a whole lot less when you look at the portion
of Americans who consider themselves independent.
From 2008 to mid-2016, 41% of
Americans on average considered
themselves to be members of neither
major party. In distant second place
were the 32% of Americans calling
themselves Democrats, trailed by
Republicans at 27%.
Still, the truth is that most people calling themselves
independents admit that they lean toward one party
over the other. And when it comes to which way
independents lean, it’s been a wash since 2008. The
difference between blue-leaning and red-leaning
independents averaged less than a tenth of a point.
In 2008 Democrats and Democrat-
leaners made up 50% of Americans,
and that’s before adding in true
independents that also voted in their
favor. Then the 2012 election saw
them get close to repeating that 50%
mark again.
Now, it's not like independents fit neatly in the
middle ground between the views offered by the
two parties. True, some people don't identify with
a party because they see it as not being centrist or
moderate enough.
But others view it as being too centrist. Some don't
affiliate because they dislike the party leadership,
politicians, or tactics. Others because they are just
apathetic or disillusioned with politics in general.
Democrats averaged a
5-point lead, which
isn’t shabby, but also
isn’t anywhere close to
claiming a majority.
When you take these
trends together, it’s clear
that the Democratic
Party had an easier time
winning elections than
Republicans.
Even when Republicans had big wins in the 2010 and 2014 midterm elections,
those victories were not due to definitive advantages over the Democrats in
popular support -- they were virtually tied. The midterm results were due to
voter turnout and the choices of true independents on election day. If that’s
what your wins look like, you should be nervous.
Both parties do the math
and figure out how best to
gain new supporters and
energize their base.
What these numbers show is that the
Republican Party has struggled in
recent years to appeal broadly enough
to win the party affiliation game.
